<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="528" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="44.[195,1404,279,788]" pageId="44" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,308,279,312]" pageId="44" pageNumber="528">Habitat.</emphasis>
Amazonian lowlands mostly below elevations of 
<quantity box="[1043,1134,279,312]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="44" pageNumber="528" unit="m" value="300.0">300 m</quantity>
but up to almost 
<quantity box="[201,300,319,352]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="44" pageNumber="528" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[458,577,319,352]" name="Ecuador" pageId="44" pageNumber="528">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. Specific habitats of Patton’s Nectar Bat are mainly mature and secondary rainforests but also clearings and plantations. It might prefer to fly in lower forest strata.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
